│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                  │
│                                                              │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------              │
│ The root cause is the incorrect handling of a PHI node that  │
│ is one of its own incoming values (a direct backedge). The   │
│ `getConstant` function recursively calls itself on the       │
│ incoming values, and when it encounters the PHI node itself, │
│ it doesn't have a value for it yet and the logic breaks      │
│ down. The fix is to explicitly check for this self-reference │
│ case. If an incoming value to a PHI is the PHI itself, we    │
│ should skip it in this initial computation. This allows the  │
│ iterative fixed-point analysis of the pass to correctly      │
│ determine the PHI's value over loop iterations, rather than  │
│ immediately collapsing it to an incorrect state.             │
│                                                              │
│ I will add a condition around the `mergeIn` call:            │
│                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ // If the incoming value is the PHI itself, don't merge it   │
│ in. This                                                     │
│ // will be handled by the fixed-point iteration.             │
│ if (PN->getIncomingValue(i) != PN)                           │
│   Result.mergeIn(getConstant(PN->getIncomingValue(i)));      │
│ ```                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ This prevents the incorrect merge that leads to the          │
│ `overdefined` state and subsequent miscompilation.           │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------              │
